	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Major expansion of production in LDCs anticipated</h1>

			
			<h4>
												01 July 2009
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>Press reports indicate that over the next ten years Sudan is looking to increase sugar production from 850,000 tonnes to 13 million tonnes. This comes on the back of new investments from a Moroccan company which will generate 43,000 tonnes of new sugar production.</p><p>Meanwhile Illovo has announced its intention of launching a rights issue ‘to raise cash to fund expansion in Africa’, with the expansion expected to take place largely in Zambia, Mozambique, Mali and Malawi. This expansion of production in LDCs mirrors a contraction in Illovo’s production in South Africa. Illovo’s South Africa operations contributed ‘19% to profit, Malawi 45%, Zambia 12%, Swaziland 9%, Tanzania 9% and Mozambique 6%’. The expanded sugar production is intended to position Illovo ‘to benefit from duty-free, quota-free access to the EU sugar market from October 2009’. Indeed, press reports suggest that Illovo is looking to boost exports to the EU from its Zambian subsidiary by 30% from October 2009. Illovo’s annual report indicates that ‘exports into premium-priced markets are very important to the group’s business and sugar sales into these markets were around 220,000 tonnes’ last year.</p><p>Sudan and Mozambique are seen by the ISO as the two ACP countries most likely to benefit from the reformed EU sugar regime, while Caribbean producers are deemed most likely to ‘miss out’. Tanzania and Zimbabwe are also likely to benefit. Southern Africa is seen as ‘one of the lowest-cost production regions in the world’, although significant issues of land ownership and investment mobilisation will need to be addressed in fulfilling production potential. Production in ACP preferential suppliers is expected to rise to ‘9.5 million tonnes by 2014 from 7 million tonnes in 2008-09’. Exports could reach 3.5 million tonnes, up from 1.9 million tonnes in 2007-08, although not all of this sugar will be destined for the EU market. Some ACP countries will find it more profitable to supply regional markets. Nevertheless ‘the value of sugar exports to the EU by preferential exporters is expected to total €1.04 billion in 2014-15, up 24% from the level in 2005-06’, according to ISO representatives.</p><p>Looking beyond the LDCs, in 2009 the Mauritian sugar sector is projecting a 6% expansion of production to 480,000 tonnes, from 452,062 tonnes in 2008. In the coming period the Mauritian sugar industry expects to export up to 400,000 tonnes of sugar annually to the EU market under a new agreement reached in 2008 with ‘Europe’s largest sugar company, Germany’s SuedZucker’.</p>
		
		
